&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from Unite the Union (HCS0008)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The death of four offshore oil and gas workers returning from the Borgsten Dolphin platform
[normal],
[normal] after their helicopter transfer ditched in the waters off the south Shetland coast on the evening of August 23
[normal]rd
[normal] 2013, provoked further questions into the safety o
[normal]f helicopters serving offshore installations on the UK Continental Shelf (UKCS).  
[normal]1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the immediate aftermath of August’s tragedy Unite was inundated with the concerns expressed by our offshore membership regarding their confidence in the safety of the 
[normal]UK 
[normal]offshore oil and gas sector 
[normal]helicopter fleet, specifically regarding the 
[normal]various 
[normal]Super Puma types manufactured by the French firm Eurocopter. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As a direct
[normal] response to this, Unite launched our ‘Back Home Safe’ campaign calling on Oil &amp; Gas UK (OGUK) to 
[normal]address t
[normal]he 
[normal]lack of confidence in 
[normal]the serving
[normal] helicopter fleet
[normal] through the implementation of the following demands: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In conjunction, 
[normal]Unite 
[normal]also 
[normal]conducted an extensive consultation with our membership a
[normal]nd the wider offshore workforce; a 
[normal]survey of over 
[normal]one thousand
[normal] offshore oil and gas 
[normal]employees (
[normal]the results of 
[normal]which will be 
[normal]presented in this submission) on the issue of helicopter safety.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Through the extensive nature of our consultation we 
[normal]believe
[normal] that our findings accurately reflect the concerns and views of offshore workers across 
[normal]the UK offshore oil and gas sector 
[normal]with regards to helicopter transfer safety. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As a result, 
[normal]Unite is 
[normal]very clear
[normal] that any 
[normal]detailed 
[normal]review of UK helicopter safety 
[normal]- particularly offshore helicopter commercial transfers - 
[normal]must 
[normal]incorporate the views of the offshore workforce and we believe this submission should compel Committee Members to begin that process.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Approximately 75 helicopters serve the UKCS for offshore commercial transfer purposes with three main operators: Bond; Bristow; and CHC, collectively operating upwards of 50,000 flights a year. There are two key manufacturers providing helicopters to the i
[normal]ndustry; Eurocopter and Sikorsky. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Eurocopter Super Puma AS332 L type, AS332 L1 type, AS332 L2 type and EC225 type provide approximately 50 per cent of the service provision.  The remaining 50 per cent are Sikorsky S-92 type helicopters. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]August’s di
[normal]tching was the fifth such incident in four years and the death of four people raised the total number of fatalities to twenty, with sixteen people having perished off the Aberdeenshire coast in April 2009
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Since February 2009 there have been five major incidents involving the transfer of offshore workers 
[normal]to or 
[normal]from installations in the UKCS: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Our comparative offshore helicopter safety record with our North Sea neighbour Norway makes for unfavourable reading
[normal] and t
[normal]he disparity in safety records between the UK and Norway is often cited by offshore 
[normal]workers as a long-standing concern
[normal]. This is more than justified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the last decade, since 2002, the UK offshore oil and gas industry has suffered 
[normal]38 fatalities[bold] involving offshore helicopter transfers. There have been 
[normal]zero[bold] 
[normal]fatalities[bold] attributed to 
[normal]offshor
[normal]e 
[normal]helicopter transfers in Norway over the last decade with the last such incident in 1997, claiming 12 lives.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Leading academics, like Andrew Watterson, Professor of Health Effectiveness at the University of Stirling, has suggested the Norwegian success c
[normal]an be attributed to occupational health and safety structure laws developed in 2000, specifically the Norwegian 
[normal]Work Environment Act
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unite believes that in the wake of these recent fatalities and against the backdrop of the last decade
[normal] 
[normal]the industry
[normal] should follow the Norwegian example,
[normal] given the obvious environmental similarities due to its geographical proximity, 
[normal]driven by the
[normal] objective of 
[normal]creating 
[normal]a world leading safety record on offshore helicopter safety. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The ‘Back Home Safe’ Campaign will act
[normal] as a driver for this, amplifying the collective voice of Unite’s offshore members and also the wider workf
[normal]orce to ensure both industry and government does more to protect the industry’s most important asset – 
[normal]its
[normal] people. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The sample[bold]3.1.1
[normal]              
[normal]Over 1,100 workers were interviewed representing a cross section of the offshore workforce. Responses were received from workers employed on over 100 different offshore installations.  
[normal]3.1.2
[normal]              
[normal]62.1% of respondents were employed 
[normal]on a permanent basis in the Oil &amp; G
[normal]as Industry and
[normal] 37.9% gave their employment status as ad-hoc, or non permanent.  
[normal]3.1.3
[normal]              
[normal]Respondents
[normal] had on average 12 years 
[normal]of employment
[normal] in the industry.  Responders were both union members, 46.6% and non union members, 
[normal]53.4%. 
[normal]3.1.4
[normal]              
[normal]The gender of those responding was not recorded. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The results[bold]3.2.1 
[normal]              
[normal]Overwhelmingly helicopters are the main mode of transport offshore,  99.1%. With the average number of flights undertaken annually 
[normal]per worker approximately 
[normal]28.6. The 
[normal]majority fly less than 40 helicopter flights annually but a significant minority of workers fly more frequently with 188 workers taking over 40 flights annually.
[normal]3.2.2
[normal]              [bold]Two manufacturers, 
[normal]Eurocopter and 
[normal]Sikorsky, 
[normal]and 
[normal]two models of helicopter, Sikorsky S-92 
[normal]and Eurocopter 
[normal]Super Puma 
[normal]EC22
[normal]5 dominiate the North Sea fleet – they 
[normal]can accurately be described as the workhorses of the industry. 
[normal]3.3.3
[normal]              [bold]When workers were asked, ‘
[normal]Which make and model of helicopter do you fly in most frequently?’ 
[normal]Sikorsky S-92 was the st
[normal]ated by 57.0% of workers. The next most frequent response was Eurocopter EC225 42.7%. 
[normal]Other 
[normal]significant models and types stated were the Eurocopter AS 332 L1 &amp; L2 (7.1 &amp; 17.1%).
[normal]3.3[bold].[bold]              [bold]Worker confidence in offshore flights[bold]3.3.1
[normal]              
[normal]In response to the 
[normal]question
[normal],
[normal] ‘At the present moment how confident are you in the safety of offshore helicopter flight?’ over 45% stated they were not confident. This figure incresed to over 53% when those who did n
[normal]ot give an opinion are excluded:
[normal]3.3.2
[normal]              
[normal]When subsequently asked
[normal],
[normal] ‘In the past 12 months has your level of confidence in helicopter flight offshore increased, decreased or stayed the same?’ 
[normal]o
[normal]ver 77% of workers stated
[normal] that their confidence had decreased. Less than 1% of the workforce said that
[normal] their confidence had increased:
[normal]3.3.3
[normal]              
[normal]When the confidence of workers is examined for each of the most commonly used 
[normal]helicopters (
[normal]TABLE 1[bold]). The results show significant different levels of confidence in each of the 5 most commonly flown in helicopters, (Sikorsky S-92s and Eurocopter EC225s, AS 332 L, L1s &amp; L2s). Workers have a higher level of confidence in the Sikorsky S
[normal]-92s. It is only this make and model in which the number of workers confident is greater than the number of workers who are not confident, although even for the S-92s 41.1% are not confident. 
